
[1]fold

   FOLD, n. [See the verb, to fold.]

   1. A pen or inclosure for sheep; a place where a flock of sheep is
   kept, whether in the field or under shelter.

   2. A flock of sheep. Hence in a scriptural sense, the church, the flock
   of the Shepherd of Israel.

   Other sheep I have, which are not of this fold. John 10.

   3. A limit. [Not in use.]

                                  FOLD, n.

   1. The doubling of any flexible substance, as cloth; complication; a
   plait; one part turned or bent and laid on another; as a fold of linen.

   2. In composition, the same quantity added; as two fold, four fold, ten
   fold, that is, twice as much, four times as much, ten times as much.

   FOLD, v.t. [Heb. The primary sense is to fall, or to lay, to set, throw
                             or press together.]

   1. To double; to lap or lay in plaits; as, to fold a piece of cloth.

   2. To double and insert one part in another; as, to fold a letter.

   3. To double or lay together, as the arms. He folds his arms in
   despair.

   4. To confine sheep in a fold.

    FOLD, v.i. To close over another of the same kind; as, the leaves of
                               the door fold.
